Just happened to come across this as I wrote a class that parses sprite sheets.  We call `Texture2D.GetData` only on loading a sprite sheet, and only to extract metadata embedded in the pixel data of a png file.  Here is an example of what we're doing:

```
int dataWidth, dataHeight, dataX, dataY;
Texture2D source;
// variables are set between declaration and call to GetData
// dataX < dataWidth <= source.Width
// dataY < dataHeight <= source.Height
// source always contains a valid image

var colors = new Color[dataWidth * dataHeight];
// fails on the following line with IndexOutOfRangeException:
source.GetData(0, new Rectangle(dataX, dataY, dataWidth, dataHeight), colors, 0, dataWidth * dataHeight);
```

On DirectX (and presumably Android), the call to `GetData` succeeds with the expected data.  Using GL (the `#else` condition in the source code), I consistently get `IndexOutOfRangeException` on larger sprite sheets (in excess of 800x800).

I managed to get it working by changing Graphics/Texture2D.cs in `Texture2D.GetData<T>(int, Rectangle?, T[], int, int)`:

```
   var temp = new T[this.width*this.height];
   GL.GetTexImage(TextureTarget.Texture2D, level, this.glFormat, this.glType, temp);
-  int z = 0, w = 0;
+  int z = 0, w;

   for(int y= rect.Value.Y; y < rect.Value.Y+ rect.Value.Height; y++) {
+      w = 0;
       for(int x=rect.Value.X; x < rect.Value.X + rect.Value.Width; x++) {
           data[z*rect.Value.Width+w] = temp[(y*width)+x];
           w++;
       }
       z++;
   }
```

Is the absence of `w = 0` in the outer `for` loop intentional?  I'm a bit confused.

